We recommended, and the Management agreed to:
Require the Municipal Accountant to:
Effect necessary adjusting entries to reclassify all completed infrastructure projects still recorded under the CIP accounts to their appropriate PPE accounts;
Exert effort to identify the projects under the CIP-TF account, especially regarding their completion status, so that they can be properly reclassified or appropriate adjusting entries can be made;
Compute the corresponding depreciation expense and accumulated depreciation for all completed projects as of December 31, 2024, and adjust the affected accounts;
Closely coordinate with the Municipal Engineer to obtain the status of ongoing projects to properly classify the asset accounts as of year-end.
Require the Municipal Engineer to continuously update the Municipal Accountant on the status of accomplishments of public infrastructure projects to ensure accurate presentation of related accounts in the financial statements.

We recommended and the Management agreed to direct the following actions:
The Acting-Municipal Treasurer to prepare a Schedule of Unreleased Checks as of year-end and ensure its timely submission to the Municipal Accountant;
The Municipal Accountant to issue a Journal Entry Voucher (JEV) to restore the unreleased checks as of year-end to the Cash in Bank- Local Currency, Current Account, based on the schedule provided and recognize the corresponding liability/payable account;
The Acting-Municipal Treasurer to verify the status of stale checks amounting to ₱1.271 million and inform the Municipal Accountant of reversion if warranted; and
The Municipal Accountant to revert the stale checks as of year-end based on the status provided by the Acting Municipal Treasurer.

We reiterated our recommendations and the Management agreed that the Municipal Mayor:

Direct the Municipal Accountant, in coordination with the General Services Office to investigate on the discrepancy noted, reconcile the amounts recorded in the books with the RPCPPE and effect the necessary adjustments;

Require the General Services Officer to prepare and maintain the Property Cards (PC) for all PPE accounts;

Direct the Municipal Accountant to determine the specific details of the undepreciated PPEs and recognize depreciation expense for all depreciable PPE items;

We further recommended and the Management agreed that the Municipality will avail of the one-time cleansing of PPE accounts as provided under Commission on Audit (COA) Circular No. 2020-006 to finally establish PPE balances that are verifiable as to existence, condition and accountability.

We recommended and the Management agreed that the Municipal Mayor instruct the MENRO-Designate and personnel concerned to:

Submit copy of the 10-year SWM Plan, as approved by the National Solid Waste Commission and regularly update the SWM plan to ensure sustainability, viability and effectiveness and relevance to the Solid Waste Management of the Municipality;

Refrain from collecting unsegregated wastes from the barangay MRFs and expedite the approval of the Contract of Agreement for the provision of garbage disposal services and to commence the disposal of residual wastes of the Municipality, once the contract has been approved;

Intensify the Information Education and Communication campaign on Solid Waste Management and educate the constituents of the waste segregation at source; and

Address the issue of power requirement of the equipment used in the Eco-Park and initiate strategies in the reduction of wastes of the Municipality.

We recommended and the Management agreed that the Municipal Mayor:

Facilitate the installation and implementation of the CSC-approved PMS, in accordance with the CSC circulars issued for the purpose;

Create an Agency/Office Performance Management Teams (PMTs) who will determine the list of qualified personnel to be granted with the Step Increment Due to Length of Service;

Direct the OIC-HRMO to inquire with the Civil Service Commission (CSC) on the Municipality’s condition in the grant of Step Increment Due to Length of Service;

Direct the OIC-Municipal Budget Officer to compute the Personal Service (PS) Cap/Limitation of the Municipality taking into consideration the supposed implementation of Step Increment to ensure that excess in PS will not be incurred; and

Implement the Step Increment Due to Length of Service based on the guidelines provided under CSC-DBM Joint Circulars No. 1, s. 2012 and No. 1, s. 2016.

We also recommended that the Municipal Mayor:

Create an Appraisal Committee composed of the Municipal Assessor, Engineer, Accountant and Treasurer to facilitate the appraisal of the value of the parcels of land owned by the Municipality;

Direct the Municipal Accountant to reconcile and correct the records of land properties of the Municipality;


Direct the Municipal Accountant to reconcile and maintain Property, Plant and Equipment Ledger Cards for the land account; and

Direct General Services Officer to maintain Property Cards for the parcels of land and also the real properties owned by the Municipality.

We recommended and the Management agreed that the Municipal Mayor require the:

Municipal Accountant and OIC-Municipal Budget Officer to maintain separate registries for the QRF, CO and MOOE of the LDRRMF;


Municipal Accountant to set up a Special Trust Fund (STF) in the Trust Fund books and determine the correct amount of unexpended DRRMF-MOOE for CY 2020 and 2021 to be transferred to the STF and facilitate the transfer of fund;

xxx

Open a separate bank account for the LDRRMF where all the accumulated unutilized funds will be deposited.

Furthermore, we recommended that at the end of the year, the unexpended balance of the LDRRMF be transferred to a special trust fund solely for the purpose of supporting DRRM activities, and may be utilized for new expenditures upon submission of a revised AIP as approved by the local sanggunian and LCE upon recommendation of the MDRRMC.

We recommended that the Local Chief Executive direct the following:

The Municipal Accountant to reconcile the Municipality’s records with that of the DILG RO-VI, and effect the necessary adjustments in the books of accounts, if any, to present the correct amount of liabilities in the financial statements;

The Acting Municipal Treasurer to return to the DILG RO-VI the unexpended balance of the fund transfer upon completion of the project.

We recommended that the LCE direct:

The Municipal Accountant and Acting Municipal Treasurer to monitor the receipts and corresponding disbursements of funds, ensure the completeness of the liquidation reports and supporting documents, in accordance with Section 3.1.2 of COA Circular No. 2012-001, and submit the same to the IPG and IA Audit Team, if such projects are already implemented;

The OIC - Municipal Engineer to undertake the procurement process for the unimplemented projects, and immediately implement these within the prescribed period agreed in the MOA, with strict compliance to the provisions of RA No. 9184 and its Revised IRR, as well as budgeting, accounting, and auditing rules and regulations; and;

The Acting Municipal Treasurer to refund/return to the IPG the unexpended balance of the fund transfer upon completion of the project.

We recommended and the Municipal Mayor agreed to direct the:
Municipal Accountant, in coordination with the General Services Office to investigate on the discrepancy noted, reconcile the amounts recorded in the books with the RPCPPE and effect the necessary adjustments;
GSO and Accounting Office to prepare and maintain the Property Cards (PC) and PPE Ledger Cards, respectively, for all PPE accounts;
Municipal Accountant to reclassify the erroneous entries made pertaining to the overhauling of ambulance from Motor Vehicle to Other Transportation Equipment, and from Office Equipment to the appropriate Machinery and Equipment account on the purchase of desktop computers, CCTV and Quick Extensive SMS Alert System; and
GSO to follow the prescribed format of Property Sticker, as provided for in COA Circular No. 2020-006.

We also reiterated our recommendation and the Municipal Mayor agreed to implement the one-time cleansing of PPE accounts as provided for under COA Circular No. 2020-006, to finally establish the PPE balances that are verifiable as to existence, condition and accountability.

We recommended and the Municipal Mayor agreed to direct the:
OIC-Municipal Assessor to fast track the processing of the Certificate of Title of the 33 parcels of land owned by the Municipality to establish absolute ownership and protect the interest of the Municipality over those lots;
General Services Officer to ascertain the actual use of land by conducting a physical inspection of Land owned by the Municipality;
Municipal Accountant to reconcile and maintain Real Property Ledger Cards for the land account and correct the records of land properties of the Municipality if warranted; and
Inventory General Services Officer to maintain Property Cards for the parcels of land and other real properties owned by the Municipality.

We recommended and the Municipal Mayor agreed to instruct the:
Acting-Municipal Treasurer to prepare a Schedule of Unreleased Checks as at year-end and provide the same to the Municipal Accountant;
Municipal Accountant to issue a Journal Entry Voucher (JEV) reverting the unreleased checks as at year-end to the Cash in Bank- Local Currency, Current Account based on the schedule provided by the Municipal Treasurer and recognize the corresponding liability/payable account;
Acting-Municipal Treasurer to verify the status of stale checks amounting to ₱0.962 million and inform the Municipal Accountant for its reversion if warranted;
Municipal Accountant to revert the stale checks as at year-end based on the status provided by the Acting Municipal Treasurer; and
Acting-Municipal Treasurer to ensure that checks are released to the payees by indicating the actual date of receipt in the Disbursement Vouchers.

We recommended and the Municipal Mayor agreed to:
Direct the concerned officers and employees to stop the practice of reimbursement or direct purchase of goods and services;
Designate a Petty Cash Custodian and establish a Petty Cash Fund for authorized petty or miscellaneous expenses, taking into consideration the guidelines set forth under COA Circular No. 2012-001 dated June 14, 2012;
Direct the Program Coordinator to provide a conservative estimate of the number of attendees/participants in the program or activity to be implemented and conduct the proper procurement process of meals and snacks prior to the commencement of the said program or activity; and
Direct the Municipal Accountant to ensure that all disbursements are duly supported with complete documentary requirements.

Henceforth, we recommended and the Municipal Mayor, thru the Bids and Awards Committee, agreed to strictly adhere to the provisions of RA No. 9184 and its 2016 Revised IRR.

We recommended and the Municipal Mayor agreed to direct the:
Municipal Accountant to ensure that travel claims are supported with complete and appropriate supporting documents before processing its reimbursements or granting the cash advance and acknowledging the corresponding liquidation;
Municipal Accountant to only allow payment for taxi fares incurred during official travels of the municipal officials and employees if supported with taximeter receipts;
Municipal officials and employees to secure travel orders from the appropriate approving officers covering their entire itinerary of travel, including the travel time allotted before and after the seminars, trainings, meetings, and the like; and
We further recommended and the Municipal Mayor agreed to submit certification from the Provincial Governor as to the absolute necessity of his claim for actual accommodation expenses, if any, and refund the excess of the allowable amount.

We recommended and the Municipal Mayor agreed to:
Re-constitute and strengthen the GAD Focal Point system and capacitate its members by sending them or providing them the necessary training relative to the Gender and Development (GAD);
Direct the GFPS to develop and maintain LGU GAD Database as source of information for gender-responsive planning, programming and policy formulation;
Direct the concerned personnel to submit the GAD Plan and Budget (GPB), duly reviewed and endorsed by the DILG to the Audit Team and to follow strictly the provision of PCW-DILG-DBM-NEDA JMC No. 2013-01; and
Ensure the full implementation of GAD PPAs identified, utilize the allocated budget for GAD to maximize the funds and ensure that the relevant GAD PPAs will address/respond to the gender-related issues identified in the Municipality.

We recommended and the Management agreed that the Municipal Mayor direct the:

Acting-Municipal Treasurer to enforce collection of the delinquent real property taxes by conducting more aggressive tax campaign and by strictly implementing the remedies provided in Sections 256 to 260 of R.A. No. 7160;

Municipal Assessor, in coordination with the Acting-Municipal Treasurer, to conduct assessment of all real properties in the Municipality, determine those properties that belong to the government for cleansing, and correct the possible duplication of records.

We recommended and the Management agreed that the Municipal Mayor require the concerned personnel to submit the following: 

Basis in the computation of the honoraria granted in CY 2022;

Office Order creating and designating the BAC composition and authorizing the members to collect honoraria;

Minutes of BAC Meeting;

Notice of award to the winning bidder of procurement activity being claimed;

Certification that the procurement involves competitive bidding; and

Attendance sheet listing names of attendees to the BAC meeting.

Henceforth, we recommended and the Management agreed that the Municipal Mayor thru the Bids and Awards Committee and the Municipal Accountant strictly adhere to the provisions of DBM Budget Circular No. 2004-5A in the grant of their honoraria.

We recommended the following:

The LCE together with the department heads to establish effective internal control measures starting from the planning and budgeting process to the disbursement process to ensure that government funds are utilized appropriately and efficiently in accordance with the rules and regulations governing various government transactions; 


The OIC-Municipal Accountant to investigate the composition of the liabilities, present and submit the subsidiary ledgers with complete details and supporting documents to check whether such liabilities are already past due, to be settled within the year or long term in nature in order to properly present the correct balances in the financial statements or make necessary adjustments, if any.

We recommended that the Local Chief Executive direct the concerned municipal officials and employees to:

Prepare a duly accomplished GAD Plan and Budget together with appropriate supporting documents in accordance with the prescribed procedures and guidelines for GAD Planning and Budgeting;

Submit the GPB to the Provincial Planning and Development Office for review and submit the corrected GPB to the Office of the Provincial Director, DILG for endorsement;

Monitor and evaluate the implementation of the annual GAD Plan and Budget through the preparation and submission of the GAD Accomplishment Report together with necessary documents; and

Ensure the full utilization of the allocated budget and propose plans/ programs for GAD to maximize the funds and benefits thereof and ensure that the relevant LGU PPAs and GAD activities will address/respond to the gender issues identified.

Strictly adhere to the provisions of JMC No. 2013-01 of the PCW, DILG, DBM and NEDA.

We recommended that the Local Chief Executive direct the concerned officials and employees to:

a. Establish a Special Trust Fund for the unexpended/unobligated balance of the QRF and DRRMF-MOOE;


b. Open a separate bank account for the LDRRMF where all the accumulated unutilized funds will be deposited; and

1.	The Municipal Accountant and Acting Municipal Treasurer account for the exact amount of undeposited collections of the previous Acting Municipal Treasurer and recommend to the Municipal Mayor to demand its return/deposit;

2.	The Municipal Mayor exhaust all means to demand the return of the undeposited collections from the previous Acting Municipal Treasurer; and

3.	The concerned accountable officers deposit all collections intact and in full amount with the authorized depository bank in accordance with the policies and procedures under PD No. 1445 and COA Circular No. 92-382.

(AAR 2019 Finding No. 3;
AAR 2018 Finding No. 6)

We recommended and the management agreed to formulate an action plan to implement the audit recommendations and submit immediately the AAPSI form to the audit team, and likewise furnish the DBM, the Speaker of the House of Representatives, the President of the Senate of the Philippines, the House Committee on Appropriations and the Senate Committee on Finance, either in printed form or by way of electronic document, a copy of the said report and ensure that said status report is posted in the Municipality’s website as mandated by Section 99 of R.A. No 11260.

(AAR 2019 Finding No. 23;
AAR 2018 Finding No. 19)

We recommended the following:

a. The Local Chief Executive (LCE) to direct the concerned Municipal officials and employees to liquidate and/or refund immediately their unused cash advances pursuant to the provisions of Section 339 of RA 7160 in relation with Section 89 of PD No. 1445, and COA Circulars Nos. 97-002 and 96-004, to avoid accumulation of unliquidated cash advances and to attain a fair presentation of the relevant accounts in the financial statements;

b. The Municipal Accountant to adhere to pertinent provisions and ensure that no cash advances shall be allowed to any official or employee unless the previous cash advance granted is settled or a proper accounting thereof is made;

c. The LCE to direct the imposition of appropriate sanctions for the unjustified failure of the concerned Municipal officials and employees to liquidate their cash advances; 

d. The Municipal Accountant to acknowledge and record liquidations of cash advances upon submission of complete supporting documents equivalent to the amount granted. If the money advanced is not fully utilized, require refund of the unspent amount evidenced by an Official Receipt before recording the settlement; and 

e. The Municipal Accountant to reconcile their records relative to the grant, utilization and liquidation of cash advances and prepare necessary adjusting entries to correct the balances of unliquidated cash advances.

f. The Accountable Officers to use the cash advance solely for the specific legal purpose for which it was granted and not incur expenses in excess of the authorized amount granted.

We recommended the following:


a. The Local Chief Executive (LCE) to direct the OIC-Municipal Budget Officer, Acting Municipal Treasurer and OIC-Municipal Accountant to comply with the requirements of RA No. 7160 and PD No. 1445 with regards to proper fiscal administration practices in the Municipality as well as find ways and means to address the cash deficit and exercise diligence, prudence and proper control in the disposition of government funds;

b. The LCE together with the department heads to establish effective internal control measures starting from the planning and budgeting process to the disbursement process to ensure that government funds are utilized appropriately and efficiently in accordance with the rules and regulations governing various government transactions; 

d. The OIC-Municipal Accountant to investigate the composition of the liabilities, present and submit the subsidiary ledgers with complete details and supporting documents to check whether such liabilities are already past due, to be settled within the year or long term in nature in order to properly present the correct balances in the financial statements or make necessary adjustments, if any; and

e. The LCE together with the department heads to improve/intensify collection efforts and deposit accordingly cash collected to improve the Municipality’s cash position that can meet its obligations.

We recommended that the Local Chief Executive direct:

a. The Municipal Accountant to ensure that all claims against government funds are supported with complete documentation pursuant to Section 4(6) of PD No. 1445;

b. The Bids and Awards Committee to strictly adhere to the provisions of the Revised IRR of RA No. 9184 by ensuring that all procurement shall be done in accordance with the prescribed guidelines;

c. The officials concerned to pay the disbursements of procured goods and services through checks instead of paying out of the cash advances of the Disbursing Officer; and


d. The Acting Municipal Treasurer to ensure that only duly appointed/designated Disbursing Officers perform disbursing functions.

We recommended that the Local Chief Executive direct the concerned municipal officials and employees to:

a. Prepare a duly accomplished GAD Plan and Budget together with appropriate supporting documents in accordance with the prescribed procedures and guidelines for GAD Planning and Budgeting;

b. Submit the GPB to the Provincial Planning and Development Office for review and submit the corrected GPB to the Office of the Provincial Director, DILG for endorsement;

c. Monitor and evaluate the implementation of the annual GAD Plan and Budget through the preparation and submission of the GAD Accomplishment Report together with necessary documents; and

d. Ensure the full utilization of the allocated budget and propose plans/ programs for GAD to maximize the funds and benefits thereof and ensure that the relevant LGU PPAs and GAD activities will address/respond to the gender issues identified.

e. Strictly adhere to the provisions of JMC No. 2013-01 of the PCW, DILG, DBM and NEDA.

We recommended the following:

a. The LCE, together with the members of the MDRRM Council, to implement strictly the PPAs for disaster mitigation, prevention and preparedness contained in the LDRRMFIP and utilize accordingly the LDRRMF  in conformity with the guidelines of the NDRRMC, DBM and DILG JMC  No. 2013-1, to achieve the maximum benefits for the Municipality’s constituents;

c. The LCE to direct the OIC-Municipal Accountant to transfer the unexpended/ unobligated balance of the QRF and DRRMF-MOOE to the Special Trust Fund under the account Trust Liability-DRRM in the Trust Fund books, and discuss the details of such in the Notes to the Financial Statements.

We recommended that the Municipality:

Require and/or observe the strict implementation of mandatory segregation of solid wastes from source to disposal facility;

b. Establish MRF that includes solid waste transfer station or sorting station, drop-off center, composting facility and recycling facility.

