a. The Municipal Accountant and Acting Municipal Treasurer to monitor the receipts and corresponding disbursements of funds, ensure the completeness of the liquidation reports and supporting documents, in accordance with Section 3.1.2 of COA Circular No. 2012-001, and submit the same to the IPG and IA Audit Team, if such projects are already implemented;

b. The OIC - Municipal Engineer to undertake the procurement process for the unimplemented projects,  and immediately implement these within the prescribed period agreed in the MOA, with strict compliance to the provisions of RA No. 9184 and its Revised IRR, as well as budgeting, accounting, and auditing rules and regulations; and;

c. The Acting Municipal Treasurer to refund/return to the IPG the unexpended balance of the fund transfer upon completion of the project.

The Municipality was not able to achieve its projected revenue for CY 2018 with a shortfall of P9,830,110.86; and revenue code and ordinances that have not been revised or updated since CY 1993 were used as basis for collections of taxes and fees, thereby casting doubts as to the propriety of taxes and fees imposed and the controls adopted in order to raise and collect additional revenue to support its programs, projects and activities that may benefit its constituents.

We recommended that the LCE direct the concerned Municipal Officials to:

a. Set more realistic forecasting of revenue, taking into account prior years’ experiences and other relevant factors and statistics as aid in setting targets;

The Municipality was not able to comply with the requirements of: (a) implementing the  mandatory segregation of solid wastes; and  (b)  establishing an efficient Materials Recovery Facility (MRF) contrary to the pertinent provisions of RA No. 9003, thus exposing its constituents to the risk of environmental and health hazards.

We recommended that the Municipality:

Require and/or observe the strict implementation of mandatory segregation of solid wastes from source to disposal facility;

